FOUR schools are still closed in Lavender Hill, Cape Town after gang violence flared up in the area last week.It is understood three people have suffered strokes as a result of the trauma of being caught up in the fighting.A News24 user said teachers decided to lock the schools to keep everybody out of the area for their own safety, while bullets whizzed past the school grounds.''The school, sometimes the learners' only sanctuary, found itself in the middle of this gang war,'' said the concerned user, who asked not to be named.One teacher even had to hide inside the school safe because gun shots were going off near her classroom window.Pupils in matric were too traumatised to write an important exam paper, the source said.The Western Cape Education Department confirmed that Lavender Hill High School, Levana Primary School, Hillwood Primary School and Prince George Primary School are still closed.Spokeswoman Millicent Merten said a meeting was held in Ottery yesterday to discuss the situation with police.Comment was not immediately available from the police.&nbsp;http://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/gang-fighting-forces-closure-of-four-cape-town-schools-20170530